Instead, shouldnâ€™t one assessment have 6 or 7 viewpoints from 6 or 7 experts, including that of the patient?

I mean really! Why do we put a patient through 6 or 7 separate assessments (especially patients who have experienced trauma), just so each discipline gets to complete their assessment for their intervention?
MDT working should be the norm not the exception. Each member of the team working in a way that facilitates the specialities adding their parts to the overall assessment.

My opinion is that despite so much evidence suggesting MDT working has better outcomes for patient experience and outcomes we are still in practice really not great at being inclusive of everyoneâ€™s expertise, and this needs to change.

The mental health act itself is also a barrier as ultimately there will always be a responsible clinician. That some (not all I hasten to add), clinicians feel is a barrier to MDT working and co-production when ultimately they are the ones who will be held accountable.

In real terms there has to be a buy in from all members of the MDT to make it work yet we still have a very medically led service in psychiatry, that in some instances makes it very difficult to facilitate a change to the status quo.

So, in real practice why is this way of working, so difficult to achieve?  
Lots of working in siloâ€™s with little feeding back, daunting for some patients to meet the whole MDT in one setting if we invited all to reviews. Workload pressures of teams preventing attendance anyway.

Next point, as a non-medical clinical lead being a member of a multi-disciplinary team full of expertise is essential & helps give a 360 view of how we can support the patient to achieve their outcomes. I like to think that we all have an equally valuable view of support needed.

First point, and Iâ€™d appreciate your views - the patient is a member of the MDT, as we encourage co-production patients own expertise is of great value, and we should be equally embracing input from all members.
